# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: siem-logging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] An **audit trail** (also called **audit log**) is a security-relevant chronological record, set of records, and/or destination and source of records that provide documentary evidence of the sequence of activities that have affected at any time a specific operation, procedure, event, or device.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Audit records typically result from activities such as financial transactions, scientific research and health care data transactions, or communications by individual people, systems, accounts, or other entities.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The process that creates an audit trail is typically required to always run in a privileged mode, so it can access and supervise all actions from all users; a normal user should not be allowed to stop/change it.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Furthermore, for the same reason, the trail file or database table with a trail should not be accessible to normal users.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Another way of handling this issue is through the use of a role-based security model in the software.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The software can operate with the closed-looped controls, or as a 'closed system', as required by many companies when using audit trail functionality.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In telecommunications, the term means a record of both completed and attempted accesses and service, or data forming a logical path linking a sequence of events, used to trace the transactions that have affected the contents of a record.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In information or communications security, information audit means a chronological record of system activities to enable the reconstruction and examination of the sequence of events and/or changes in an event.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Information put away or transmitted in paired structure that might be depended upon in court.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] An audit trail is a progression of records of computer data about a working framework, an application, or client exercises.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Computer frameworks may have a few audit trails each gave to a specific sort of action.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Related to proper apparatuses and systems, audit trails can help with distinguishing security infringement, execution issues and application issues.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Routine log audits and investigation are valuable for distinguishing security episodes, approach infringement, fake movement, and operational issues soon after they have happened, and for giving information valuable to settling such issues.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Audit logs can likewise be valuable for performing forensic investigation, supporting the associations inside examinations, setting up baselines, and distinguishing operational patterns and long run issues.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In nursing research, it refers to the act of maintaining a running log or journal of decisions relating to a research project, thus making clear the steps taken and changes made to the original protocol.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In accounting, it refers to documentation of detailed transactions supporting summary ledger entries.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] This documentation may be on paper or on electronic records.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In online proofing, it pertains to the version history of a piece of artwork, design, photograph, video, or web design proof in a project.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In clinical research, server based systems such as clinical trial management systems (CTMS) require audit trails.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Anything regulatory or QA/QC related also requires audit trails.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In pharmaceutical manufacturing, it is a Good Manufacturing Practice regulatory requirement software generate audit trails, but not all software have audit trail functionality built-in.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The first 'generic' audit trail generating software came out late 2021.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The software is called Audit Trail Control, capable of fulfilling regulatory requirements for any software used in pharmaceutical manufacturing.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In voting, a voter-verified paper audit trail is a method of providing feedback to voters using a ballotless voting system.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] In employment and human resources contexts, audit trails provide a documented record of investigative steps taken, including complaint intake, witness interviews, and remedial actions taken, specifically in cases involving allegations of misconduct, discrimination or harassment.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), employers are required to conduct a "prompt and adequate investigation" and take "appropriate action based on the findings," making a reviewable audit trail central to demonstrating compliance.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] Multiple regulatory frameworks require organizations to maintain audit trails for compliance purposes.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement hardware, software, and procedural mechanisms that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] These audit controls, specified under the technical safeguards at 45 CFR 164.312(b), must capture information such as user logins, file accesses, and modifications to ePHI.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to review audit logs at least once every 30 days to detect unauthorized access or other security incidents.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires publicly traded companies to maintain adequate internal controls over financial reporting, which in practice necessitates comprehensive audit trails for financial transactions and system access.
[src:siem-logging/audit-trail] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data through logging mechanisms.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:siem-logging/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet is focused on providing developers with concentrated guidance on building application logging mechanisms, especially related to security logging.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Many systems enable network device, operating system, web server, mail server and database server logging, but often custom application event logging is missing, disabled or poorly configured.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It provides much greater insight than infrastructure logging alone.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Web application (e.g. web site or web service) logging is much more than having web server logs enabled (e.g. using Extended Log File Format).
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should be consistent within the application, consistent across an organization's application portfolio and use industry standards where relevant, so the logged event data can be consumed, correlated, analyzed and managed by a wide variety of systems.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should always be included for security events.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logs are invaluable data for both security and operational use cases.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Process monitoring, audit, and transaction logs/trails etc. are usually collected for different purposes than security event logging, and this often means they should be kept separate.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The types of events and details collected will tend to be different.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example a PCIDSS audit log will contain a chronological record of activities to provide an independently verifiable trail that permits reconstruction, review and examination to determine the original sequence of attributable transactions.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It is important not to log too much, or too little.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Use knowledge of the intended purposes to guide what, when and how much.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The remainder of this cheat sheet primarily discusses security event logging.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application itself has access to a wide range of information events that should be used to generate log entries.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Thus, the primary event data source is the application code itself.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application has the most information about the user (e.g. identity, roles, permissions) and the context of the event (target, action, outcomes), and often this data is not available to either infrastructure devices, or even closely-related applications.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The degree of confidence in the event information has to be considered when including event data from systems in a different trust zone.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Data may be missing, modified, forged, replayed and could be malicious – it must always be treated as untrusted data.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider how the source can be verified, and how integrity and non-repudiation can be enforced.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications commonly write event log data to the file system or a database (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications installed on desktops and on mobile devices may use local storage and local databases, as well as sending data to remote storage.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Your selected framework may limit the available choices.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] All types of applications may send event data to remote systems (instead of or as well as more local storage).
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This could be a centralized log collection and management system (e.g.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] SIEM or SEM) or another application elsewhere.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether the application can simply send its event stream, unbuffered, to stdout, for management by the execution environment.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider separate files/tables for extended event information such as error stack traces or a record of HTTP request and response headers and bodies.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The level and content of security monitoring, alerting, and reporting needs to be set during the requirements and design stage of projects, and should be proportionate to the information security risks.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This can then be used to define what should be logged.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] There is no one size fits all solution, and a blind checklist approach can lead to unnecessary "alarm fog" that means real problems go undetected.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Each log entry needs to include sufficient information for the intended subsequent monitoring and analysis.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It could be full content data, but is more likely to be an extract or just summary properties.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application logs must record "when, where, who and what" for each event.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For more information on these, see the "other" related articles listed at the end, especially the comprehensive article by Anton Chuvakin and Gunnar Peterson.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Never log data unless it is legally sanctioned.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, intercepting some communications, monitoring employees, and collecting some data without consent may all be illegal.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Never exclude any events from "known" users such as other internal systems, "trusted" third parties, search engine robots, uptime/process and other remote monitoring systems, pen testers, auditors.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] However, you may want to include a classification flag for each of these in the recorded data.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider using personal data de-identification techniques such as deletion, scrambling or pseudonymization of direct and indirect identifiers where the individual's identity is not required, or the risk is considered too great.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In some systems, sanitization can be undertaken post log collection, and prior to log display.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It may be desirable to be able to alter the level of logging (type of events based on severity or threat level, amount of detail recorded).
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] If your development framework supports suitable logging mechanisms, use or build upon that.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, implement an application-wide log handler which can be called from other modules/components.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Document the interface referencing the organisation-specific event classification and description syntax requirements.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] If possible create this log handler as a standard module that can be thoroughly tested, deployed in multiple applications, and added to a list of approved and recommended modules.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Where possible, record data in a standard format, or at least ensure it can be exported/broadcast using an industry-standard format.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In some cases, events may be relayed or collected together in intermediate points.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In the latter some data may be aggregated or summarized before forwarding on to a central repository and analysis system.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] As an example, the diagram below shows a service that provides business functionality to customers.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] We recommend creating a centralized system for collecting logs.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] There may be many such services, but all of them must securely collect logs in a centralized system.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, all external requests from users go through the API management service, see application in MIDDLEWARE 2 segment.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] As you can see in the image above, at the network level, the processes of saving and downloading logs require opening different network accesses (ports), arrows are highlighted in different colors.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Also, saving and downloading are performed by different applications.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Enable processes to detect whether logging has stopped, and to identify tampering or unauthorized access and deletion (see protection below).
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The logging mechanisms and collected event data must be protected from mis-use such as tampering in transit, and unauthorized access, modification and deletion once stored.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Logs may contain personal and other sensitive information, or the data may contain information regarding the application's code and logic.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In addition, the collected information in the logs may itself have business value (to competitors, gossip-mongers, journalists and activists) such as allowing the estimate of revenues, or providing performance information about employees.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This data may be held on end devices, at intermediate points, in centralized repositories and in archives and backups.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether parts of the data may need to be excluded, masked, sanitized, hashed, or encrypted during examination or extraction.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] See `NIST SP 800-92` Guide to Computer Security Log Management for more guidance.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Log data, temporary debug logs, and backups/copies/extractions, must not be destroyed before the duration of the required data retention period, and must not be kept beyond this time.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Legal, regulatory and contractual obligations may impact on these periods.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Because of their usefulness as a defense, logs may be a target of attacks.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] See also OWASP Log Injection and CWE-117.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] A confidentiality attack enables an unauthorized party to access sensitive information stored in logs.
[src:siem-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Which information should be modifiable by whom?
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:siem-logging/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Many systems and applications which run on a computer network generate events which are kept in event logs.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] These logs are essentially lists of activities that occurred, with records of new events being appended to the end of the logs as they occur.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Protocols, such as syslog and SNMP, can be used to transport these events, as they occur, to logging software that is not on the same host on which the events are generated.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] The better SEMs provide a flexible array of supported communication protocols to allow for the broadest range of event collection.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Although centralised logging has existed for long time, SEMs are a relatively new idea, pioneered in 1999 by a small company called E-Security, and are still evolving rapidly.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] The key feature of a Security Event Management tool is the ability to analyse the collected logs to highlight events or behaviors of interest, for example an Administrator or Super User logon, outside of normal business hours.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] This may include attaching contextual information, such as host information (value, owner, location, etc.), identity information (user info related to accounts referenced in the event like first/last name, workforce ID, manager's name, etc.), and so forth.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] This contextual information can be leveraged to provide better correlation and reporting capabilities and is often referred to as Meta-data.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Products may also integrate with external remediation, ticketing, and workflow tools to assist with the process of incident resolution.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] The better SEMs will provide a flexible, extensible set of integration capabilities to ensure that the SEM will work with most customer environments.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] SEMs are often sold to help satisfy U.S. regulatory requirements such as those of Sarbanes–Oxley, PCI-DSS, GLBA.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] One of the major problems in the SEM space is the difficulty in consistently analyzing event data.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Every vendor, and indeed in many cases different products by one vendor, uses a different proprietary event data format and delivery method.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] Even in cases where a "standard" is used for some part of the chain, like Syslog, the standards don't typically contain enough guidance to assist developers in how to generate events, administrators in how to gather them correctly and reliably, and consumers to analyze them effectively.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] As an attempt to combat this problem, a couple of parallel standardization efforts are underway.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] First, The Open Group is updating their circa 1997 XDAS standard, which never made it past draft status.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] This new effort, dubbed XDAS v2, will attempt to formalize an event format including which data should be included in events and how it should be expressed.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] The XDAS v2 standard will not include event delivery standards but other standards in development by the Distributed Management Task Force may provide a wrapper.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] In addition, MITRE developed efforts to unify event reporting with the Common Event Expression (CEE) which was somewhat broader in scope as it attempted to define an event structure as well as delivery methods.
[src:siem-logging/security-event-manager] The project, however, ran out of funding in 2014.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:siem-logging/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:siem-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
